.TH RUFUSARM64 1 "20 July 2026" "RufusArm64 0.12.1" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
rufusarm64 \- graphical bootable USB creator and guarded data-media formatter for Ubuntu ARM64
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B rufusarm64
.RI [ --persistence ]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B rufusarm64
opens the graphical RufusArm64 application. It creates raw Linux media and
supported Windows installation USB media after explicit target confirmation
and administrator authentication.
.PP
The ordinary Create USB action preserves supported Linux raw/ISOHybrid images
byte-for-byte. Persistent-live creation is a separate guarded workflow.
.PP
The separate
.B Restore / format...
action erases the selected removable drive, removes any existing boot layout,
and creates one verified data-only partition using GPT or MBR and FAT32,
exFAT, NTFS, or ext4. RufusArm64 first runs an unprivileged dry-run, displays
the exact device identity, geometry, filesystem, label, required tools, and
warnings, and requires the generated FORMAT phrase before administrator
authentication. The graphical path cannot enable fixed-disk override or bypass
guarded unmounting.
.PP
Cancellation is reported precisely. A cancellation before erasure leaves the
drive unchanged. Cancellation or failure after erasure may leave incomplete
media that must be formatted again before use. A successful report confirms
the partition geometry and filesystem readback but explicitly does not claim
that the result is bootable.
.PP
After the main image writer finishes, RufusArm64 keeps the selected image and
shows explicit next steps. The completed medium can be left unchanged, another
copy can be created after choosing a different removable drive, or the exact
operation target can be passed to Restore drive for storage. That restoration
still performs a fresh identity-bound, unprivileged plan and requires the exact
FORMAT phrase before any erase. Failed or cancelled writes are conservatively
reported as potentially incomplete and are never reformatted automatically.
.PP
The separate
.B FreeDOS...
action erases the selected removable drive and creates deterministic FreeDOS
1.4 media from the package's checksum-pinned kernel and FreeCOM payload. It
plans without elevation, binds the refreshed device identity and capacity,
requires 512-byte logical sectors, displays the exact MBR/FAT32 geometry and
platform warnings, and requires the generated
.B WRITE FREEDOS 1.4 TO /dev/DEVICE FOR X86 BIOS LEGACY
phrase before administrator authentication. The graphical path exposes no
fixed-disk override or guarded-unmount bypass.
.PP
FreeDOS media created by this action is limited to x86-compatible processors
using BIOS or UEFI Legacy/CSM firmware. It does not boot ARM64 or UEFI-only
systems. Complete structural readback and SHA-256 verification do not prove
that a particular physical computer will boot the drive.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.B --persistence
Open the guarded persistent Ubuntu/Debian live-USB creator directly.
.SH SAFETY
Every selected target is erased. Verify the device model, capacity, and path
shown in the final confirmation dialog. A successful write or byte comparison
does not prove that particular firmware will boot the media.
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR rufusarm64-cli (1),
.BR rufusarm64-nonbootable-format (1),
.BR rufusarm64-freedos-format (1),
.BR rufusarm64-persistence (1)
